0":"1140–1200","1166–1218":"1166–1218","1166–1250":"1166–1250","1185–1244":"1185–1244","1192–1257":"1192–1257","–1214":"–1214","–1146":"–1146","–Female":"Overleden","before 1166":"vóór 1166","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","1140":"1140","1192":"1192","1214":"1214","1257":"1257","1146":"1146","1244":"1244","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","from 1145 to 1160":"van 1145 to 1160","from 1189 to 1200":"van 1189 to 1200","about 1166":"circa 1166","1218":"1218","Gistel, West Flanders, Belgium":"Gistel, West-Vlaanderen, België","Europe":"Europa"},"en":{"from 1145 to 1160–from 1189 to 1200":"from 1145 to 1160–from 1189 to 1200","1145–1200":"1145–1200","1140–1200":"1140–1200","1166–1218":"1166–1218","1166–1250":"1166–1250","1185–1244":"1185–1244","1192–1257":"1192–1257","–1214":"–1214","–1146":"–1146","–Female":"Deceased","before 1166":"before 1166","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","1140":"1140","1192":"1192","1214":"1214","1257":"1257","1146":"1146","1244":"1244","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","from 1145 to 1160":"from 1145 to 1160","from 1189 to 1200":"from 1189 to 1200","about 1166":"about 1166","1218":"1218","Gistel, West Flanders, Belgium":"Gistel, West Flanders, Belgium","Europe":"Europe","nameMeanings":[{"name":"van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Gistel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["North German and Danish: from a personal name based on ancient Germanic <i>gīsil</i> ‘pledge, hostage, noble youth’ (see   Giesel  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Giesel","meanings":["German: from the personal name <i>Giesel</i>, a short form of any of several ancient Germanic personal names with the first element <i>gīsil</i> ‘pledge, hostage, noble offspring’. In ancient and medieval ancient Germanic society, the younger children of kings and princes were sometimes sent to be brought up at the court of a neighboring ruler, as a pledge of peace between the two nations or clans. Thus, the male personal name <i>Gisil</i> and its feminine equivalent <i>Gisela</i> mean both ‘pledge’ and ‘noble offspring’."]}]},{"name":"Arnoud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Arnold</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Arnoud van Gistel was born from 1145 to 1160, in Gistel, West Flanders, Belgium as the son of Baudouin de Ghistelles Chevalier and Nn Nn. He married Agnès de Voormezele van Herzeele before 1166, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. He died from 1189 to 1200, in his hometown."},"et":{"from 1145 to 1160–from 1189 to 1200":"1145 kuni 1160–1189 kuni 1200","1145–1200":"1145–1200","1140–1200":"1140–1200","1166–1218":"1166–1218","1166–1250":"1166–1250","1185–1244":"1185–1244","1192–1257":"1192–1257","–1214":"–1214","–1146":"–1146","–Female":"Surnud","before 1166":"enne 1166","1185":"1185","1250":"1250","1140":"1140","1192":"1192","1214":"1214","1257":"1257","1146":"1146","1244":"1244","1200":"1200","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","from 1145 to 1160":"1145 kuni 1160","from 1189 to 1200":"1189 kuni 1200","about 1166":"umbes 1166","1218":"1218","Gistel, West Flanders, Belgium":"Gistel, West-Vlaanderen, Belgia","Europe":"Europe"},"fi":{"from 1145 to 11